00:02:45.679 --> 00:02:52.880
So let's go into the past just for a little while. So way back in 2018, early 2018, we looked at

00:02:53.440 --> 00:02:58.399
a number of table packages available in R. I was surprised. There was quite a few. I thought there

00:02:58.399 --> 00:03:04.320
was five. There's more than that. So we looked at all of them. And we noticed they had strengths

00:03:04.320 --> 00:03:09.039
in different areas. Some were known to be a bit domain specific. You know, heavy on the

00:03:09.039 --> 00:03:13.520
stats summary stuff. While others are more general. You can just do whatever you want.

00:03:15.119 --> 00:03:19.440
We noticed that most handled one, maybe two, sometimes a few output formats. So I'm talking

00:03:19.520 --> 00:03:28.800
like HTML, you know, just text, stuff like that. So we saw these and we thought, can we innovate

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:33.279
in this area at all? And yeah, we thought we could. We wanted to make something gt plot like.

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:39.679
We wanted to focus on noninteractive tables that delivered camera ready output in a wide variety

00:03:39.679 --> 00:03:45.839
of formats. So we had a few core requirements before we even sort of started, you know,

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:51.919
making gt. So the first thing we had to have was a declarative but forgiving API.

00:03:52.639 --> 00:03:59.199
So, you know, things we have today are from this. Like, we should always start a gt table

00:03:59.199 --> 00:04:05.919
with the gt function. Any statements could be expressed in any order, give or take.

00:04:05.919 --> 00:04:11.360
Order sometimes matters. But usually not. And each function should act as instructions.

00:04:11.919 --> 00:04:15.279
Gt should then figure out what to render. So it will sort of reconcile

00:04:15.919 --> 00:04:20.160
what you expressed and render the table in the right way.

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:27.519
We wanted to have table generation in multiple output types with the same API. So the same set

00:04:27.519 --> 00:04:33.359
of statements supplied here, gt should always work when taking the same code used for HTML.

00:04:34.079 --> 00:04:36.959
And, you know, you can also make a LaTeX table with the same code.

00:04:37.119 --> 00:04:42.720
We really wanted powerful formatters for cell values. So take, for example, this

00:04:42.720 --> 00:04:48.000
unformatted column of values. We want to have things like formatting to an exact number of

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
decimal places, formatting as integers, handling rounding and things like that,

00:04:52.959 --> 00:04:59.519
changing separators, the digit separators, a way to express values in scientific notation,

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:05.519
a way to use percent signs, perhaps not scaling, ways to force the percent

00:05:05.679 --> 00:05:12.320
the positive sign so it can show changes. We want to have significant digits. That's

00:05:12.320 --> 00:05:18.880
kind of hard to create numbers like that. We wanted to have great support for things

00:05:18.880 --> 00:05:24.320
like currencies, you know, expressing values as bytes, even decorating values using a pattern.

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:28.559
We wanted it to be flexible and have values formatted the way you wanted them to be.

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:35.040
We also wanted to have it so you can experiment in the API, like move columns to the right,

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:42.320
move columns around, you know, have GT do things for you, like group columns together

00:05:42.320 --> 00:05:45.920
if they're united under a single spanner, or you can just move columns manually.

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:53.760
We really wanted footnotes. That's a thing we didn't see too much of in other table packages,

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:58.320
but we know it's a thing and we wanted to have it in there. We wanted them to be pain-free.

00:05:59.359 --> 00:06:03.519
So we didn't want you to have to worry about them and manually sort of reorder them.

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:08.640
First of all, we wanted it to be straightforward to define table footnotes.

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:13.279
Then we wanted the ordering to be sort of automatic. And the more advanced features

00:06:13.279 --> 00:06:17.839
are things that are just expected in footnotes, like we should be able to apply the same footnote

00:06:17.839 --> 00:06:23.200
to multiple locations. And if you have multiple footnotes at one location, that should be allowed

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:27.440
and it should handle the numbering or lettering, you know, in the right way.

00:06:28.399 --> 00:06:38.640
So, you know, we worked away at it in most of 2018. We released it in 2018. We had HTML as,

00:06:38.640 --> 00:06:42.640
like, the main output format, but we had LaTeX and RTF as experimental output types.

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:48.880
Since then, we had tons of conversations with people on social media, inside GitHub issues,

00:06:49.519 --> 00:06:53.920
and through lots of customer conversations. And through those conversations, we learned

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:59.600
pretty quickly what was, you know, what was working and what wasn't working at all with GT.

00:07:01.119 --> 00:07:07.679
So we got to work on fixing stuff. So we improved the RTF output support. We improved LaTeX,

00:07:07.679 --> 00:07:11.920
because, you know, they weren't too good at the beginning. We added additional cell formatters,

00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:16.079
like these ones right here, and we improved the existing cell formatters as well, added more

00:07:16.079 --> 00:07:21.679
options. We provided more ways to style cells, which was very important. It's what people wanted.

00:07:22.480 --> 00:07:26.320
And we had various other quality of life improvements and API enhancements.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.239
Okay. In terms of those customer conversations with people, we had lots of those with people

